{{Portal|Communism|Latin America}} The '''First Conference of the Communist Parties of Latin America''' was in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], June 1–12, 1929.{{sfnm |1a1=Carr |1y=1978 |1p=982 |2a1=Miller |2y=1989 |2p=40}} Thirty-eight delegates, representing Argentina, [[Brazil]], [[Bolivia]], [[El Salvador]], [[Guatemala]], [[Cuba]], [[Colombia]], [[Ecuador]], [[Mexico]], [[Panama]], [[Paraguay]], [[Peru]], [[Uruguay]], and [[Venezuela]], took part in the meeting. The only established [[communist party]] in the region that did not participate was the [[Communist Party of Chile]], which at time suffered a period of harsh repression under the government of [[Carlos Ibáñez del Campo]].{{sfn|Guerra|Prieto|1980|p=9}}
The conference agreed on an analysis of the Latin American political development, considering that the revolution in Latin America ought to be [[anti-imperialism|anti-imperialist]], [[agrarianism|agrarian]], and [[democracy|democratic]]. The conference also committed itself to an accord of solidarity with the [[Soviet Union]].{{sfn|Guerra|Prieto|1980|p=9}}
[[Ronaldo Munck]], Ricardo Falcón, and Bernardo Galitelli wrote that the conference "set the '[[Third Period]]' course for Latin American [[communism]] as a whole."{{sfn|Munck|Falcón|Galitelli|1987|p=105}}
